{"title_page": "1 Signal Regiment (United Kingdom)", "text_new": "{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name = 1 Signal Regiment, Royal Signals\n| image = \n| dates = 1905\u20131992<br/>1993\u2013Present\n| country = {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n| branch = {{army|United Kingdom}}\n| type = [[Military Communications|Signals]]\n| role = \n| size = [[Regiment]]\n| command_structure = [[11th Signal Brigade and Headquarters West Midlands]]\n| garrison = [[Stafford]]\n| nickname = \n| battles = \n| commander1 = \n| commander1_label = \n| commander2 = \n| commander2_label = \n| Cite = \n}}\n'''1 Signal Regiment''' is a [[military communications]] regiment of the [[British Army]]. The regiment is now part of the [[11th Signal Brigade and Headquarters West Midlands|11th Signal Brigade]] and provides signal support to two armoured infantry brigades.\n\n== History ==\nThe regiment's antecedents date to the formation of the 1st Division, Telegraph Battalion, [[Royal Engineers]], in 1905.  From 1905 to 1960, the regiment names changed several times, for example, from 1st Divisional Signal Company to 1st Divisional Signal Regiment. After the [[1957 Defence White Paper]], the army was re-organized and the regiment was re-titled as 1st Division Headquarters and Signal Regiment, and was moved to [[Verden an der Aller|Verden]] in 1978.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The British Army in Germany (BAOR and After): An Organizational History 1947 \u2013 2004|last=|first=|publisher=Graham E. Watson and Richard A. Rinaldi|year=2005|isbn=0-9720296-9-9|location=|pages=67}}</ref><ref>Isby and Kamps; Rinaldi BAOR.</ref> After this move the regiment remained as part of the [[1st (United Kingdom) Division|1st Armoured Division]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=The British Army in Germany: An Organizational History 1947\u20132004|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=88}}</ref> In 1993 after the [[Options for Change]] force reductions, the [[1st Armoured Division (United Kingdom)|1st Armoured Division]] was disbanded,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The British Army in Germany (BAOR and After): An Organizational History 1947 \u2013 2004|last=|first=|publisher=Graham E. Watson and Richard Rinaldi|year=2005|isbn=0-9720296-9-9|location=|pages=115}}</ref> becoming HQ Lower Saxony District.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=The British Army in Germany: An Organizational History 1947-2004|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=115}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=The British Army in Germany: An Organizational History 1947-2004|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=135}}</ref>\n\nAfter 1st Armoured Division was disbanded, several months elapsed before [[4th Armoured Division (United Kingdom)|4th Armoured Division]] was redesignated 1st Armoured Division.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=The British Army in Germany (BAOR and After): An Organizational History 1947 \u2013 2004|last=|first=|publisher=Graham E. Watson and Richard Rinaldi|year=2005|isbn=0-9720296-9-9|location=|pages=117, 135}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=Royal Corps of Signals : Unit Histories of the Corps (1920-2001) and Its Antecedents|publisher=Helion and Company|year=2003|isbn=1 874622 92 2|location=West Midlands, United Kingdom|pages=26}}</ref>  In accordance with this change, the former 4th Armoured Division HQ and Signals Regiment was redesignated 1 (UK) Armoured Division Headquarters and Signal Regiment in late 1993.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Royal Corps of Signals : Unit Histories of the Corps (1920\u20132001) and Its Antecedents|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=23\u201326}}</ref>  Before the initial [[Army 2020]] reforms, the regiment was the divisional support signals regiment that supported and helped the communications for the entire [[1st (United Kingdom) Division|1st (UK) Armoured Division]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140427141823/https://www.army.mod.uk/signals/25255.aspx|title=1 (UK) ADSR \u2013 British Army Website|date=11 January 2019|website=www.army.mod.uk|archive-date=27 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Army 2020 Refine]] reforms the regiment was titled as 1 Signal Regiment, and was transferred to the [[11th Signal Brigade and Headquarters West Midlands|11th Signal Brigade]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.army.mod.uk/who-we-are/formations-divisions-brigades/force-troops-command/hq-11th-signal-and-west-midlands-brigade/|title=HQ 11th Signal and West Midlands Brigade|website=www.army.mod.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-12-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.royalsignalsmuseum.co.uk/royal-signals-regiments/|title=Royal Signals Regiments {{!}} Royal Signals Museum|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-12-30}}</ref> Under Army 2020 Refine, the regiment will support to a Strike Brigade as a close support signal communications regiment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://royalsignals.org/FileTransfer/RSI-Journal/PDF/RSI-Journal-Spring-2014.pdf|title=Royal Signals Journal|date=8 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.royalsignalsmuseum.co.uk/royal-signals-regiments/|title=Royal Signals Regiments {{!}} Royal Signals Museum|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-01-08}}</ref>\n\n== Organisational Structure ==\nStructure as a result of the initial [[Army 2020]] reforms:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://royalsignals.org/FileTransfer/RSI-Journal/PDF/RSI-Journal-Spring-2014.pdf|title=Royal Signals Association Update|date=8 January 2019|website=royalsignals.org|page=44}}</ref>\n\n* 200 Squadron\n*[[Queen's Gurkha Signals|246 Gurkha Signal Squadron]]\n* Support Squadron\n\n== Alliances ==\n*{{flag|Germany}} \u2013 Panzergrenadier Division Signal Regiment Fernmeldebataillon 1<ref name=\":2\" />\n*{{flag|Canada}} \u2013 1st Canadian Signal Regiment<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Regiments of the Royal Corps of Signals|1st Signal Regiment, Royal Signals]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1905]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox mi